               <msContents>
                  <summary change="#add-summary"> A nearly complete, unillustrated volume of the
                        <title>Nafā'is al-Funūn fī ‘Arā'is al-‘Uyūn</title> (Troves of the Arts in
                     the Eyes of the Brides) by Ilkhanid-era author Shams al-Dīn Muḥammad ibn Maḥmūd
                     Āmulī (d. ca. 1352). A famous encyclopedia describing one hundred and twenty
                     different arts, the author modelled his work on another well-known medieval
                     encyclopedia, <title>Durrat al-Tāj</title> (Pearl of the Crown) by Quṭb
                     al-Shīrāzī (ca. 1236–1311). Several different hands copied this volume, which
                     suffered damage, loss, and extensive replacement of the pages. </summary>

                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_369-item1">
                     <author key="person_289849308" ref="http://www.viaf.org/viaf/289849308/"
                        change="#ids-cleanup">
                        <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Shams al-Dīn Muḥammad ibn
                           Maḥmūd Āmulī</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="ar">شمس الدين محمد ابن محمود آمولي‏</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" key="work_6927">Nafā'is al-Funūn fī ‘Arā'is
                        al-‘Uyūn</title>
                     <title xml:lang="ar" key="work_6927">نفائس الفنون في عرائس العيون</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa" type="basmalla">
                        <locus from="1b" to="1b">برگ ۱پ (Folio 1b):</locus> حمد و ثنا و شکری بی
                        منتها حضرت پادشاهی را که افکار ازکیا و انظار عقلا در پیدای ظلمت و معرفت
                        گیریای اواز قصور ادراک هر دم ندای سبحانك ماعرفانك میدهند... </incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa">
                        <locus from="313b" to="313b">برگ ۳۱۳پ (Folio 313b):</locus> ... هشت در دارد
                        چندان سیب بر داشت که بر هر در چون نیمه‌‌ٔ آنچه با او بود بوقتی که بیرون آمد
                        یک سیب با او پیش نماند آن سیبها چند بوده باشد دویست و پنجاه و شیش بوده باشد
                        و الله اعلم بالصواب. </explicit>
                     <colophon xml:lang="fa">
                        <locus from="313b" to="313b">برگ ۳۱۳پ (Folio 313b):</locus> تمت الکتاب
                        المسمی بنفایس الفنون مشتمل علی مایة و عشرین علماً من العلوم المتنوعه من
                        النقلیات والعقلیات بحمد الله و حسن توفیقه والصلوة والسلام علی خیر الخلقه
                        محمد و آله اجمعین. </colophon>
                     <colophon>Uninformative colophon.</colophon>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <note>For another single volume of this work held in the Rylands, see <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6627"><idno>Persian
                              MS 147</idno></ref>, and for a two-volume set, see <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6628"><idno>Persian
                              MS 148</idno></ref> and <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6629"
                        >149</ref>.</note>

                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support>Textblock of straight and cross-grained, externally sized and
                           polished, straw-coloured <material>paper</material> probably handmade in
                           the <placeName cert="high" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208"
                              key="place_7000208">Indian subcontinent</placeName> with ~8 laid lines
                           per cm and no discernible chain lines.</support>
                        <extent>
                           <measure unit="folio" quantity="484">484 folios, 6 flyleaves (ff. iv +
                              484 + ii)</measure>. <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>262</height>
                              <width>144</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>180</height>
                              <width>93</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation xml:id="original">Two sets of Hindu-Arabic numerals appear on the
                           upper-left corners of the a sides throughout.</foliation>
                        <collation>Undetermined. Probably quaternions throughout.
                              <catchwords>Catchwords</catchwords> present on most lower-left corners
                           of the b sides.</collation>
                        <condition>In fair condition, with moderate water and insect damage and
                           historical repairs throughout, and portions replaced.</condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" ruledLines="31" n="mistara"> Written in 1 column with 31
                           lines per page. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic">misṭarah</hi> hand
                           guide.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nasta_liq naskh" medium="ink"> Written in
                        various hands in <material>black</material> naskh and nasta‘līq with
                           <material>red</material> subheaders. </handNote>
                     <handNote scope="minor" script="nasta_liq" medium="ink"> Replaced folios
                        written in comparatively hasty <material>black</material> nasta‘līq with
                           <material>red</material> subheaders. </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <lb/>
                     <label>Table of Contents:</label> The <locus>third to fourth right flyleaves
                        (ff. iiia–iva)</locus> lists the contents with corresponding folio numbers.<lb/>
                     <label>Bookplates:</label>
                     <locus from="Inner_back_cover" to="Inner_back_cover">Left pastedown</locus>: <q
                        xml:lang="en">Bibliotheca Lindesiana</q> with pencilled shelfmark <q
                        xml:lang="en">1/E</q>, and <q xml:lang="en"><hi rend="strikethrough"
                           >Hamilton</hi> MSS No. <hi rend="strikethrough">286</hi></q> with the
                     name and number crossed out and <q xml:lang="en">Persian</q> and <q
                        xml:lang="en">369</q> written aside. </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1858" notAfter="1862">
                        <p>Probably rebound in <placeName cert="high"
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7002481" key="place_7002481"
                              >Multan</placeName> for former owner <persName type="supplied"
                              key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">George William
                              Hamilton</persName>.</p>
                        <p>Resewn at two stations unsupported. Flyleaves of of comparatively heavy,
                           uneven cross-grained paper added at the beginning and end. Edges trimmed
                           with chevron endbands twined in red and green silk threads over round
                           cores at <locus from="Head" to="Head">head</locus> and <locus from="Tail"
                              to="Tail">tail</locus>. Covered in full maroon-coloured goatskin
                              <material>leather</material> over <material>pasteboards</material>, tight-backed,
                           with squares along the edges, defined joints, and without a flap (Type
                           III binding per Déroche). Internal doublures of the same leather, with
                           the excess widths adhered as hinges on the first and last flyleaves to
                           connect the text to the covers, with strips of paper, zig-zag cut along one edge, applied over top to
                           disguise the joins.</p>
                        <decoNote type="binding">Internal and external board margins double-ruled in yellow. Spine bears the title in yellow nasta‘līq.</decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>176</height>
                              <width>155</width>
                              <depth>67</depth>      
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>Binding in good condition, with opening to the gutter margins
                           restricted, and white salts on the exterior probably due to prolonged exposure to moisture.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>Probably completed in the <origPlace cert="high" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208"
                     key="place_7000208">Indian subcontinent</origPlace> undated, but                 <origDate calendar="#Gregorian" cert="medium" notBefore="1600" notAfter="1800">possibly 17th century</origDate>.</origin>
                  <provenance><p>
                     Subsequently acquired by <persName type="supplied" key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">Colonel George William Hamilton (1807-1868)</persName> 
                     who served in <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208">India</placeName> <date calendar="#Gregorian" from="1823" to="1867"> from 1823 to 1867</date>, latterly as Commissioner in <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001535" key="place_7001535">Delhi</placeName>. 
                     He acquired over a thousand Indian and Persian manuscripts, from which the
                     <orgName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/134857252">British Museum</orgName> selected 352, now held in the
                     <orgName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/121814978">British Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </provenance> 
                  <provenance><p>
                     <persName role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058">
                        Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812–1880)</persName> purchased  the remainder of Hamilton's collection in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1868">1868</date>.
                  </p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName role="dnr" key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup"
                     >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                        when="1901">1901</date> from <persName role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands
                        (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908"
                           >1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands
                              Library</orgName>, <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010477"
                                 key="place_7010477">Manchester</placeName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
